# Patrick McKenzie (patio11) 
**Source:** https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=F5LYGVpgglg

--

Hi there, I'm Reid and I have here Patrick McKenzie with me at MicroConf in Prague and we're just gonna talk a little bit about email marketing.

What do you think is the most important thing about email marketing for businesses?

Honestly I think the most important thing about email marketing for businesses is that they actually do it. I know a lot of businesses which say oh yeah we know we've heard the stats, we know that email is more than any marketing channel, but we don't actually have someone who does that in our company, or we're doing it in only the most superficial manner which is doing maybe a newsletter to your entire mailing list every month.

I think that it's something that people can really see an immediate highly positive return on investment if they try to do things which are just a bit more sophisticated. For example for an e-commerce store, go to the people who bought stuff from you before, find other things that they might want to buy now, and then send them stuff and say hey you might want to buy this.

For a software company, offer people the opportunity — you're paying monthly for the software but since you plan on using it for a while, why don't you try upgrading to the annual plan and we'll give you a free month off.

One of my favorite companies doing this is called Wistia. They do online video hosting and they'll just send you an email every month saying we hear from a lot of people that they're worried they need to buy a $10,000 camera to do video — you can actually record a video on an iPhone very professionally. Here's an example of us doing an entire video on an iPhone and here's how you can do the lighting to make it look very good.

Can you speak about a specific case that you worked on where you implemented email marketing?

I was once working with a software company on something unrelated and it was 4:45 in the afternoon and we thought well we only have 15 minutes left in the day. I said wait, we can do something worthwhile in 15 minutes. Why don't you show me a list of all the customers who have a quota of 100 units monthly and show me everyone who's using more than 80 units monthly.

We had a list of their email addresses and said we're going to send all these folks an email saying hey, thanks for using our service every month. We know that you're using over 80% of your quota — you might be a little worried about that. That's not actually how we do business, but since you don't want to worry, let me just get you a little more overhead by stepping you up to the next higher plan. To make this a very easy decision we'll give you 50% off the next tier plan for the lifetime of your account if you click here right now.

You sent that email out at 4:45 and the next day they were looking at a plural percent of their annual revenue caused directly by that email.

I generally work with software companies which have increased the percentage of free trials converting into paying customers by in some cases close to double, just by having a good email retention strategy in the first month — getting started guides, letting them know the team is there for them, helping them overcome issues with using the software.

What would you recommend for somebody just starting out with emails?

The number one thing I would recommend is to first start by teaching people. Think of good content which would make a tutorial post for your blog — you can repurpose that exact content in email. Come up with a few in similar themes and say hey, if you give us your email address we'll send you a five-part guide — a free course delivered over email on the subject that we're experts about.

Just start teaching. Give people a reason to trust you, a reason to feel delight when they see your name in their inbox. Towards the end you can have a call to action which asks them to buy something or deepen their relationship with your company.

For my own lifecycle emails course, prior to even starting producing the product I created a page that said here's a 15-minute video which explains something useful for you, and I will give you the rest of that video — 45 more minutes — if you give me your email address. In addition I will also send you something you will like roughly every week to two weeks.

For the next several months I just did exactly what I promised. I'd write 2,000 words of advice on pricing, come back two weeks later with how to sell software, two weeks later engineering practices — continuing for a few months while I was building my product.

When I was about to launch I had three or four thousand on my list. When I was getting ready to launch I said okay, in about a month I'm going to release a paid product on lifecycle email. I built up anticipation over the month, then said okay folks, for those of you thinking email is really awesome but I don't know how to get started — I have a five-hour video course available which will teach you how to use lifecycle emails in your software company.

I sold about 200 copies of the course and made about $60,000 within two weeks.
